The Story¶

It's a hot day out. The air conditioner is out and our rent is coming due.
You have spent countless hours following leads. We get a call from a school that wants to dabble in machine learning. As a trial run they are willing to provide you with a moderate collection of deidentified student data and of course a small allowance. In return they expect a quality machine learning model that predicts final student grades.

The Data¶

The organization has provided a single table consisting of several thousand rows of data.
Since this is a story we have the luxury of deciding our true data model.
We will choose a true model that we aim estimate. We will choose random featrue values that generate our data. We aim to keep the feature values mostly realistic. Reality is often not so kind. python offers a number of distributions we can pull values from.

The features are labeled. The data represent values from the prior academic year. In our formulas we will features by X, with subscripts denoting respective variables.

The final course grade is modeled by the the rather complex function Y. Our task is to establish a function that maps a student to a final course grade Y(X). This willl allow the university to identify and remediate struggling students.

Consider a true model denoted by Y. Several different functions are specified below. We will use the uncommented model. We use this to generate our training data as well as perform a final evaluation of our selected model. Our feature samples are generated using numpy's random generators. The ranges may not be totally realistic. We include the addition of noise to our data model to add a depth of realism.

we do this below with a dictionary comprehension. The dictionary below has the same keys as above with each model fit to its data.¶

Any model must be evaluated. We must establish some measurement of quality for our model. Often this is context specific¶

sklearn offers a standard out of the box scoring metrics.¶

Estimating Generalized Perormance¶

We want a model that will handle unseen data effectively so long as our training data is reasonably representative of the live data we expect. Evaluating our models based only on their training performance may lead to poor performance on similar but different data. For example, we could create a model that strictly interpolates our data with a high degree polynomial. This would have zero error at the training points, but the model would be very poor performing ourside of the training set. This is called overfitting.

Rather, we should choose our model based on generalized performance. That is, we reserve some of our data for training and some of our data for testing. We base our scoring on similar, but likely distinct information.

What data should we train with? What should we evaluate with? In fact, training with more information leads to better models. We should really train with all the data we can. But first, we must choose a model type that has the best overall performance.

One strategy is to divy our data up into chunks called folds. We take turns using each fold as the test set, while using the remainder as the training data. We can score our model on each fold, giving us a distribution of model performance. This is called k-fold cross validation.

We want to avoid any evaluation being dependent on the order our data is in. To account for this we will shuffle our data, and perform cross validation repeatedly to better estimate performance.

In [81]:
shuffle_count=2
fit_times=pd.DataFrame(columns=list(models.keys()))
score_times=pd.DataFrame(columns=list(models.keys()))
test_scores=pd.DataFrame(columns=list(models.keys()))
for i in range(0,shuffle_count):
    print(i)
    shuffled_data=Data.sample(frac=1)

    shuffled_y=shuffled_data['Final Course Grade']
    shuffled_x=shuffled_data[predictor_columns]

    #Score each model on each fold.
    cv_scores={
        key:model_selection.cross_validate(models[key],shuffled_x,shuffled_y,cv=10, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error', n_jobs=7)
        for key in models.keys()
    }
    fit_times=pd.concat([fit_times,pd.DataFrame({key:cv_scores[key]['fit_time'] for key in cv_scores.keys()})])
    test_scores=pd.concat([test_scores,pd.DataFrame({key:cv_scores[key]['test_score'] for key in cv_scores.keys()})])
    score_times=pd.concat([score_times,pd.DataFrame({key:cv_scores[key]['score_time'] for key in cv_scores.keys()})])

Real Performance¶

Once we deliver our models they may see production. In this exercise, we have the luxory of generating more uncorrupted data at will. We will do this to get a final "true" performance measure of our model. The fully trained models will be used to evaluate our cross validation results.

In [83]:
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

n=100000

validation_predictor_values={
    'Attendance Percent': rng.uniform(low=0, high=100, size=n),#pick values uniformly from zero to 100
   'Course Load In Hours': rng.binomial(n=23, p=0.8, size=n),
   'Average Exam Score': rng.normal(loc=70, scale=8, size=n), 
   'Homework Average': rng.normal(loc=70, scale=8, size=n), 
   'Total Tutoring Hours': rng.binomial(n=23, p=0.8, size=n),
}
Validation_Data= pd.DataFrame(data=validation_predictor_values, columns=predictor_columns)

#There is typically some noise involved in getting our data.
Validation_Data['Final Course Grade']=Validation_Data.apply(Y, axis=1)

#Score each fully fitted model.
validation_scores={
    key:[mean_squared_error(models[key].predict(Validation_Data[predictor_columns]), Validation_Data['Final Course Grade'])]
    for key in models.keys()
    }

validation_scores_data=pd.DataFrame(validation_scores)

Closing thoughts¶

Random forest performs very well with both the estimated and "true" data for the moderate and extremely nonlinear true model. The rough interpretation is that our best model is off by about 1.4 points per prediction on average. This can make a big impact in a students life. For the extremely nonlinear model, which we did not run, the average error was about 21 points. This is not good enough. The linear model had several contendors for best compared to random forest with several under half a point error on average.. We highly suggest you run the other two models procvided. We used default parameters for all of these models and did not clean nor normalize our data. This makes a huge difference. There are a variety of additional methods we can apply to improve performance including: parameter selection, denoising, normalization, feature extraction, and hyper parameter selection. In extreme cases, we may even spread our load among multiple machines. We will continue to explore these topics in the future.
